1
00:00:16,891 --> 00:00:17,976
[Matt] <i>Who are you?</i>

2
00:00:19,185 --> 00:00:20,437
[Dex] <i>I'm Daredevil.</i>

3
00:00:21,479 --> 00:00:23,106
[man] <i>Hey, you can't be here!</i>

4
00:00:23,189 --> 00:00:24,149
[clamoring]

5
00:00:25,108 --> 00:00:26,067
[gunshot]

6
00:00:27,027 --> 00:00:29,738
[Dex] <i>Hello, Karen.</i>
<i>It's nice to see you again.</i>

7
00:00:35,118 --> 00:00:38,538
<i>I'm Daredevil. </i>[echoing]

8
00:00:48,048 --> 00:00:50,842
[Mercer over recording]
<i>Your internal compass isn't broken, Dex.</i>

9
00:00:50,925 --> 00:00:53,636
<i>It just works better</i>
<i>with a North Star to guide you.</i>

10
00:00:54,095 --> 00:00:55,555
[young Dex] <i>What if I can't find one?</i>

11
00:00:55,638 --> 00:00:57,724
[Mercer] <i>Then you'll rely</i>
<i>on our structure.</i>

12
00:00:57,807 --> 00:01:00,602
<i>A tidy physical space.</i>
<i>A disciplined vocation. </i>

13
00:01:00,685 --> 00:01:03,146
<i>You will build your life</i>
<i>on pillars of order.</i>

14
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:22,082
[theme music playing]

15
00:02:33,319 --> 00:02:34,821
[Matt] <i>If you'd just wake the hell up</i>

16
00:02:34,904 --> 00:02:37,115
<i>instead of playing right</i>
<i>into Fisk's hands.</i>

17
00:02:37,198 --> 00:02:38,533
<i>He's using you...</i>

18
00:02:38,616 --> 00:02:40,034
-Morning.
-[Lim] Morning, boss.

19
00:02:40,118 --> 00:02:41,703
[Matt] <i>...and I think you know it.</i>

20
00:02:42,996 --> 00:02:45,456
<i>So let me ask you this, Agent Nadeem...</i> <i>Who do you think is the danger here? </i>

21
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:56,134
<i>The man who attacked the </i>Bulletin
<i>dressed as Daredevil...</i>

22
00:02:56,217 --> 00:02:57,886
<i>he's in the FBI.</i>

23
00:03:00,346 --> 00:03:03,266
[Dex] <i>Hello, Karen.</i>
<i>It's nice to see you again.</i>

24
00:03:47,310 --> 00:03:48,311
[man] Hey!

25
00:03:49,979 --> 00:03:50,813
Julie!

26
00:03:51,731 --> 00:03:54,067
-Dex, stay away from me.
-Please, just hear me out.

27
00:03:54,150 --> 00:03:56,277
I'm doing this in public
so you'll feel safe.

28
00:03:56,361 --> 00:03:59,239
I'll stay right here.
I'm not coming any closer.

29
00:04:00,406 --> 00:04:01,407
Okay.

30
00:04:02,533 --> 00:04:06,746
I am so, so sorry
about how things ended the other night.

31
00:04:06,829 --> 00:04:10,083
I'm sorry for scaring you.
I just wanted to explain myself.

32
00:04:10,875 --> 00:04:13,670
When we worked together
at the suicide hotline,

33
00:04:13,753 --> 00:04:15,630
I saw the way you were with other people.

34
00:04:16,214 --> 00:04:19,467
Patient, compassionate, and I...

35
00:04:19,550 --> 00:04:21,219
[panting]

36
00:04:21,302 --> 00:04:22,887
I really need that right now.

37
00:04:23,721 --> 00:04:25,056
My life is out of control.

38
00:04:25,139 --> 00:04:28,643
I have no family,
and I'm about to lose my job...

39
00:04:28,726 --> 00:04:29,769
Please.

40
00:04:30,770 --> 00:04:33,189
I just want to talk. Anywhere you choose.
And...

41
00:04:34,315 --> 00:04:37,235
if you say no, I'll understand...

42
00:04:38,111 --> 00:04:39,737
and I'll never bother you again.

43
00:04:57,547 --> 00:04:58,589
[Matt] Agent Nadeem.

44
00:05:02,343 --> 00:05:03,344
You're late.

45
00:05:03,428 --> 00:05:05,388
I was early,
but I needed to be sure about you.

46
00:05:05,471 --> 00:05:06,472
What's his name?

47
00:05:06,556 --> 00:05:09,183
Yeah, well,
I need to be sure about you, too.

48
00:05:09,267 --> 00:05:12,228
You have a history of hurting people.
I'm not handing you a federal agent

49
00:05:12,312 --> 00:05:14,063
-if you're gonna kill him.
-I don't do that.

50
00:05:15,106 --> 00:05:19,360
The agents you beat up the other day?
One of them is still in the hospital.

51
00:05:19,444 --> 00:05:20,778
All of them just doing their jobs.

52
00:05:20,862 --> 00:05:23,114
If they'd arrested me,
there'd be no one to take down Fisk.

53
00:05:23,197 --> 00:05:25,867
If you're right about him,
taking Fisk down is our job.

54
00:05:25,950 --> 00:05:27,160
Oh, really?

55
00:05:27,243 --> 00:05:29,954
Because we both know
where he's sleeping these days.

56
00:05:30,997 --> 00:05:32,081
But I understand.

57
00:05:32,165 --> 00:05:35,460
If there's one thing we agree on, Nadeem,
it's the greater good.

58
00:05:35,543 --> 00:05:38,129
Like house incarceration
in exchange for good intel.

59
00:05:38,212 --> 00:05:41,382
Sometimes you and I have to hurt
one person to save another.

60
00:05:42,008 --> 00:05:43,217
So what's his name?

61
00:05:46,554 --> 00:05:48,264
I need your word that you won't touch him.

62
00:05:48,348 --> 00:05:50,516
My word can't mean anything to you.

63
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:52,435
But I need to hear you give it.

64
00:05:53,770 --> 00:05:57,398
Well, I need him to testify against Fisk,
so you got it.

65
00:06:01,944 --> 00:06:04,197
We're gonna slip into his place.

66
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:07,992
Look for any evidence that ties him
to the <i>Bulletin</i> attack or to Fisk.

67
00:06:08,618 --> 00:06:11,204
If we find any, we leave it where it is.

68
00:06:12,080 --> 00:06:14,248
And we set off his fire alarm
on our way out.

69
00:06:14,332 --> 00:06:17,460
The fire department arrives,
and you circumvent a search warrant.

70
00:06:17,543 --> 00:06:19,170
But if we don't find anything,

71
00:06:19,253 --> 00:06:21,130
-the guy goes on with his life.
-Spit it out.

72
00:06:21,214 --> 00:06:22,507
Who is he?

73
00:06:24,509 --> 00:06:27,136
Special Agent Ben Poindexter.

74
00:06:31,182 --> 00:06:33,810
A small decaf and whatever she's having.

75
00:06:33,893 --> 00:06:36,187
I've got mine. Thanks.

76
00:06:36,270 --> 00:06:38,272
-My regular, Richie.
-[Richie] All right.

77
00:06:39,607 --> 00:06:44,779
So, I don't know how to say this
without it sounding like an insult.

78
00:06:44,862 --> 00:06:47,240
I was never actually into you.

79
00:06:47,323 --> 00:06:50,201
Or... not the way you might have
been thinking, anyway.

80
00:06:50,284 --> 00:06:52,537
I didn't know how to talk to you.

81
00:06:53,162 --> 00:06:54,163
Okay.

82
00:06:54,705 --> 00:06:55,832
I wasn't...

83
00:06:57,166 --> 00:06:59,085
I wasn't stalking you.

84
00:06:59,168 --> 00:07:03,923
Although, I completely see
how it could have come across that way.

85
00:07:04,006 --> 00:07:07,510
I just... I wanted to be more like you.

86
00:07:10,096 --> 00:07:12,265
Do you realize
how creepy that still sounds?

87
00:07:19,897 --> 00:07:24,735
You are so good.

88
00:07:25,403 --> 00:07:28,614
And kind. And...

89
00:07:28,698 --> 00:07:31,284
You save lives as your job.

90
00:07:33,369 --> 00:07:36,539
The FBI, the army before that...

91
00:07:37,123 --> 00:07:39,709
they helped keep me
on the straight and narrow path.

92
00:07:40,293 --> 00:07:44,297
But now, without that, it's all... [sighs]

93
00:07:44,380 --> 00:07:46,757
I'm drowning in deep water,

94
00:07:46,841 --> 00:07:50,303
and I don't know whether I'm swimming
for the surface or the bottom.

95
00:07:50,386 --> 00:07:51,429
[breathes deeply]

96
00:07:51,512 --> 00:07:54,474
Dex, you need air. Breathe.

97
00:08:02,607 --> 00:08:05,151
See, that's...
that's what I'm talking about.

98
00:08:06,110 --> 00:08:08,321
You help people right themselves. I've seen you do it a hundred times.

99
00:08:10,698 --> 00:08:16,454
All I'm asking, just treat me like...
someone on the other end of the line.

100
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:22,001
What happened at the FBI?

101
00:08:23,961 --> 00:08:26,047
The bureau needed a scapegoat.

102
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:29,550
[imitates bleating]

103
00:08:31,636 --> 00:08:32,470
[chuckles]

104
00:08:33,638 --> 00:08:35,681
[both chuckle]

105
00:08:35,765 --> 00:08:36,807
[Dex groans]

106
00:08:37,433 --> 00:08:39,936
You know, what you really need
is a good therapist.

107
00:08:42,396 --> 00:08:44,982
I had one. She died.

108
00:08:46,484 --> 00:08:47,318
Oh, I...

109
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:49,654
I'm so sorry.

110
00:08:55,034 --> 00:08:57,578
Okay. I'll help you, Dex.

111
00:08:59,205 --> 00:09:01,916
But, please, do not make me regret this.

112
00:09:02,667 --> 00:09:06,712
I promise. Promise I will not.

113
00:09:08,005 --> 00:09:09,840
[cell phone vibrating]

114
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:11,342
Excuse me.

115
00:09:23,896 --> 00:09:25,356
[knock on door]

116
00:09:30,820 --> 00:09:32,613
[Foggy] Hi. Whoa!

117
00:09:32,697 --> 00:09:35,157
-Did you get any sleep at all?
-Yeah.

118
00:09:35,241 --> 00:09:36,075
No.

119
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:41,080
-You need coffee.
-Yeah.

120
00:09:42,790 --> 00:09:45,626
You ever have one of those days
where you're just, like...

121
00:09:45,710 --> 00:09:49,171
You break it down, step by step?
Just, uh...

122
00:09:50,172 --> 00:09:54,010
"Put your feet on the floor, Karen.
Just get to the sink."

123
00:09:55,761 --> 00:09:56,762
Sure.

124
00:09:56,846 --> 00:09:59,682
Generally speaking,
I don't call myself Karen, but...

125
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:02,310
Actually, no, I don't do any of that.

126
00:10:02,393 --> 00:10:03,227
[Karen scoffs]

127
00:10:05,104 --> 00:10:07,106
How are you not at the bottom
of a bottle right now?

128
00:10:07,189 --> 00:10:08,566
Because I have a theory.

129
00:10:09,233 --> 00:10:10,818
Jeez. Must be a hell of a theory.

130
00:10:11,569 --> 00:10:14,071
Fisk is giving up criminals
involved in corruption.

131
00:10:14,155 --> 00:10:15,531
He's planning to step into the void

132
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:17,617
and become the sole source
of government protection

133
00:10:17,700 --> 00:10:20,161
for all criminals in Hell's Kitchen,
maybe the city.

134
00:10:20,244 --> 00:10:22,872
And that theory
makes you want to not drink?

135
00:10:24,123 --> 00:10:26,917
Yes, because I also have a plan.

136
00:10:27,001 --> 00:10:30,004
No. No, no, Foggy, you don't have a plan.

137
00:10:30,546 --> 00:10:32,298
Do you know what happens
when you make a plan?

138
00:10:32,381 --> 00:10:34,967
Fisk has already thought of it,
and he's made it part of his plan.

139
00:10:35,051 --> 00:10:38,721
Except he has no idea that I'm onto him.
He couldn't.

140
00:10:38,804 --> 00:10:41,515
I discovered this
while looking into Marci's briefs.

141
00:10:41,599 --> 00:10:42,600
More ways than one.

142
00:10:42,683 --> 00:10:44,477
-[groans] Foggy.
-Sorry.

143
00:10:44,560 --> 00:10:48,314
The point is she was prepping
for a deposition of a corrupt IRS official

144
00:10:48,397 --> 00:10:50,441
who was providing
fraud and money laundering services

145
00:10:50,524 --> 00:10:52,068
-for the Albanians--
-No, stop.

146
00:10:53,611 --> 00:10:54,779
I can't.

147
00:10:59,325 --> 00:11:03,120
Just one more article, Karen.
That's all it'll take.

148
00:11:06,374 --> 00:11:08,584
[sighs] All right. What's this?

149
00:11:08,668 --> 00:11:10,836
The terms of Fisk's house incarceration.

150
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:15,091
If he violates any of these, zappo.
He's back in prison.

151
00:11:15,174 --> 00:11:17,093
"Zappo"? Is that a thing?

152
00:11:17,927 --> 00:11:19,345
Number three is the key.

153
00:11:20,137 --> 00:11:22,223
"Committing or conspiring
to commit a felony."

154
00:11:22,306 --> 00:11:24,850
No, no, wait. What about number six here?

155
00:11:24,934 --> 00:11:27,853
All this stuff about being charged
with a crime that predates the agreement?

156
00:11:27,937 --> 00:11:30,314
-Number six is not the plan.
-We have a good number six.

157
00:11:31,107 --> 00:11:33,943
I mean, Fisk killed his father.
That's murder.

158
00:11:34,026 --> 00:11:36,987
There's no statute of limitations.
And his mother told Ben Urich about it.

159
00:11:37,071 --> 00:11:38,906
A dead woman told a dead guy something.

160
00:11:38,989 --> 00:11:42,451
-That's not proof. It won't stick.
-[sighs] Yeah.

161
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:45,621
You know what will? Publicizing my theory.

162
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:47,998
So the FBI sees
that Fisk has violated his agreement,

163
00:11:48,082 --> 00:11:49,709
they're forced to put him back in prison?

164
00:11:49,792 --> 00:11:53,254
And they can't ignore it
if we splash it across the front page.

165
00:11:53,337 --> 00:11:54,588
And by "we," I mean you.

166
00:11:54,672 --> 00:11:57,425
The <i>Bulletin</i> won't just let a journalist
make unsubstantiated claims.

167
00:11:57,508 --> 00:11:58,509
That's not news.

168
00:11:58,592 --> 00:12:00,928
But it is news if a candidate
running for district attorney

169
00:12:01,011 --> 00:12:02,555
makes unsubstantiated claims.

170
00:12:02,638 --> 00:12:06,016
In a public forum.
Debating the incumbent DA.

171
00:12:06,684 --> 00:12:08,310
You're gonna debate Blake Tower?

172
00:12:08,394 --> 00:12:09,729
At the Hell's Kitchen Club.

173
00:12:09,812 --> 00:12:12,314
Well, it's supposed to be
prepared remarks.

174
00:12:12,398 --> 00:12:14,191
-Huh.
-They're endorsing him.

175
00:12:14,275 --> 00:12:15,818
I'm not actually on the agenda,

176
00:12:15,901 --> 00:12:18,154
but Nelson's Meats
is a member of the club, so...

177
00:12:18,237 --> 00:12:20,156
You're just gonna confront him,
out of the blue?

178
00:12:20,239 --> 00:12:22,742
Why not?
I'll catch him when he's not expecting it.

179
00:12:22,825 --> 00:12:24,118
Throw this stuff at him--

180
00:12:24,201 --> 00:12:27,204
Yeah, you get him worked up, emotional.
Provoke him.

181
00:12:28,831 --> 00:12:29,832
It could work. Yup.

182
00:12:33,836 --> 00:12:36,172
So, you'll cover the meeting?

183
00:12:37,465 --> 00:12:39,300
Yeah, I would. I just, um...

184
00:12:41,260 --> 00:12:43,554
I lost my job. So...

185
00:12:44,638 --> 00:12:45,639
What?

186
00:12:46,891 --> 00:12:49,977
Ellison loves you like family.
What did you do?

187
00:12:51,771 --> 00:12:54,398
I refused to give him
Daredevil's identity.

188
00:12:55,983 --> 00:12:56,817
Yikes.

189
00:12:56,901 --> 00:13:01,238
Okay, well,
Ellison wants Fisk as badly as we do.

190
00:13:01,322 --> 00:13:04,784
Just tell him our plan.
Watch how fast he gives you your job back.

191
00:13:04,867 --> 00:13:08,037
Then we'll hook up at the dinner later.
You're my plus one.

192
00:13:09,288 --> 00:13:10,581
I got you the salmon.

193
00:13:28,057 --> 00:13:30,309
<i>Hey. Did the landlord let you in?</i>

194
00:13:50,955 --> 00:13:53,541
[indistinct chatter]

195
00:13:58,003 --> 00:13:59,004
Dex.

196
00:14:00,589 --> 00:14:01,715
Thanks for coming.

197
00:14:02,383 --> 00:14:05,970
You made it pretty clear I had to.
What's this about?

198
00:14:07,012 --> 00:14:08,973
I have someone here
who wants to talk to you.

199
00:14:10,266 --> 00:14:11,433
Follow me.

200
00:14:29,660 --> 00:14:32,705
Dex, this is my old friend Andrea Morales.

201
00:14:34,331 --> 00:14:35,833
She's an attorney.

202
00:14:36,417 --> 00:14:39,336
The guys took up a collection
to pay for Andy's services.

203
00:14:39,420 --> 00:14:41,630
Now if you're up for it,

204
00:14:41,714 --> 00:14:44,967
she's going to sue the bureau
for wrongful suspension on your behalf.

205
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:47,303
-She can do that?
-[Morales] I can.

206
00:14:47,386 --> 00:14:49,305
And having reviewed
the details of your case,

207
00:14:49,388 --> 00:14:51,181
I fully believe that I should.

208
00:14:52,266 --> 00:14:54,643
She's on a retainer. Starting now.

209
00:14:54,727 --> 00:14:55,811
And I'm not cheap.

210
00:14:55,895 --> 00:14:58,689
The guys must really like you,
Agent Poindexter.

211
00:15:01,317 --> 00:15:03,694
You've had my back through all this?

212
00:15:04,695 --> 00:15:06,071
I don't know how to thank you.

213
00:15:07,406 --> 00:15:11,410
The guy that saved our lives doesn't
ever have to thank us for anything.

214
00:15:14,747 --> 00:15:17,082
Well, figure out the next steps,
and, uh...

215
00:15:18,626 --> 00:15:20,544
I can't wait to have you back on the team.

216
00:15:23,756 --> 00:15:25,215
I've prepared the argument.

217
00:16:33,534 --> 00:16:35,494
-[Ray] You find anything?
-[door closes]

218
00:16:35,577 --> 00:16:38,080
[Matt] He's neat. He likes order.

219
00:16:39,039 --> 00:16:41,667
So does my wife,
but she wouldn't fit in your suit.

220
00:16:45,254 --> 00:16:48,382
Everything I have on Dex
is circumstantial at best.

221
00:16:49,299 --> 00:16:51,176
I just left him. He was solid.

222
00:16:52,845 --> 00:16:56,265
I don't see a decorated agent
falling for Fisk's bullshit.

223
00:16:56,348 --> 00:16:58,267
Yeah, well, that's what Fisk does.

224
00:16:58,809 --> 00:17:00,644
Finds a weakness. Hits it hard.

225
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:02,896
When you're already on your knees,

226
00:17:02,980 --> 00:17:05,190
you've got no choice
but to fall for his bullshit.

227
00:17:06,984 --> 00:17:09,361
I bet you guys are paying
for his room service, too.

228
00:17:20,497 --> 00:17:23,083
The suit's here. I can smell it.

229
00:17:23,167 --> 00:17:24,960
What, you can smell it?

230
00:17:27,838 --> 00:17:29,506
[Matt] GSR and latex.

231
00:17:33,135 --> 00:17:35,012
Shit. I can't call a crew to crack that.

232
00:17:40,768 --> 00:17:42,102
What, you can do that?

233
00:17:42,186 --> 00:17:44,646
[Matt] Not if you keep talking, I can't.

234
00:18:05,834 --> 00:18:08,545
The suit was here. He must've moved it.

235
00:18:09,588 --> 00:18:11,090
Well, it isn't now.

236
00:18:11,882 --> 00:18:14,802
And you smelling eau de suit
won't exactly sway a judge.

237
00:18:14,885 --> 00:18:18,097
I'm telling you, Poindexter's the guy.
It was him.

238
00:18:19,139 --> 00:18:22,017
There's nothing here tying him
to Fisk or the <i>Bulletin.</i>

239
00:18:24,603 --> 00:18:25,938
We got jack shit.

240
00:18:34,571 --> 00:18:36,615
[young Dex]<i> When the crows</i>
<i>come to the birdfeeder,</i>

241
00:18:36,698 --> 00:18:38,367
<i>I kill them with rocks.</i>

242
00:18:39,409 --> 00:18:41,870
[Mercer]<i> What does it feel like</i>
<i>to watch them die?</i>

243
00:18:42,287 --> 00:18:45,332
[Morales] It probably won't even get
as far as an arbitration.

244
00:18:45,415 --> 00:18:47,626
The government tends to balk
once folks lawyer up.

245
00:18:47,709 --> 00:18:51,255
[chuckles] This is amazing.
How long do you think this will take?

246
00:18:51,338 --> 00:18:55,676
If we do everything right,
you'll be reinstated in six months.

247
00:18:55,759 --> 00:18:58,387
-Six months?
-But we'll get you back pay.

248
00:18:59,138 --> 00:19:00,889
I don't care about back pay.

249
00:19:02,015 --> 00:19:03,892
What am I going to do for six months?

250
00:19:03,976 --> 00:19:06,228
I know it seems like a stretch,

251
00:19:06,311 --> 00:19:09,189
but you've got a bright future
ahead of you in the bureau.

252
00:19:09,773 --> 00:19:11,191
Play the long game.

253
00:19:11,900 --> 00:19:14,027
[cell phone vibrating]

254
00:19:15,028 --> 00:19:16,363
Oh. I'll be right back.

255
00:19:49,479 --> 00:19:51,481
[breathing heavily]

256
00:19:53,525 --> 00:19:54,776
[line ringing]

257
00:19:56,361 --> 00:19:58,197
[automated voice]
<i>This number has been blocked.</i>

258
00:19:58,280 --> 00:19:59,573
[call disconnects]

259
00:20:07,122 --> 00:20:08,999
[Mercer]<i> Have you been</i>
<i>doing our exercises?</i>

260
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:15,464
[young Dex]<i> Yes, but then the neighbor</i>
<i>brought home a box of stray kittens.</i>

261
00:20:16,006 --> 00:20:17,132
<i>They were in the yard.</i>

262
00:20:20,052 --> 00:20:22,221
<i>I killed them with rocks, Dr. Mercer.</i>

263
00:20:23,889 --> 00:20:26,934
<i>I tried not to, but I liked it.</i>

264
00:20:28,018 --> 00:20:30,812
[distant footsteps approaching faintly]

265
00:20:31,813 --> 00:20:35,150
So the guy has issues. Serious issues.
But that doesn't mean...

266
00:20:44,159 --> 00:20:45,869
[Matt] He's here. You should go.

267
00:20:45,953 --> 00:20:48,705
No, we had a deal.
No evidence, you don't touch him.

268
00:20:48,789 --> 00:20:51,208
-[Matt] I found evidence.
-The kind that holds up in court.

269
00:20:51,291 --> 00:20:52,668
He's gonna use the suit again.

270
00:20:52,751 --> 00:20:55,545
I got the jump on him.
I can get him to tell me where it is.

271
00:20:55,629 --> 00:20:59,007
-[Ray] You gave me your word.
-[Matt] Yeah, well, I take it back.

272
00:22:02,279 --> 00:22:04,781
-We'll never get another chance like that.
-What if you're wrong?

273
00:22:04,865 --> 00:22:06,575
-I'm not wrong.
-[gun cocking]

274
00:22:10,704 --> 00:22:11,705
[Ray groans]

275
00:22:20,255 --> 00:22:22,924
The shot came from across
the alley. [groans]

276
00:22:23,008 --> 00:22:24,926
I think it came from downstairs.

277
00:22:27,888 --> 00:22:29,639
[gunshot, ricochet]

278
00:22:32,351 --> 00:22:35,020
He's... He's ricocheting the bullets.

279
00:22:36,813 --> 00:22:38,982
-[Ray] Go for the front door.
-[Matt] He's by the window.

280
00:22:39,066 --> 00:22:40,359
He's waiting for a better shot.

281
00:22:41,276 --> 00:22:42,277
How do you know?

282
00:22:44,321 --> 00:22:45,238
[gunshot]

283
00:22:51,078 --> 00:22:53,038
He's only got three more rounds.

284
00:22:53,121 --> 00:22:54,915
I'll tell you when he reloads,
and then you go.

285
00:22:54,998 --> 00:22:56,708
[panting] Okay.

286
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:02,089
-He's not calling for backup.
-No. And he won't.

287
00:23:02,172 --> 00:23:03,632
But the neighbor called 911.

288
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:09,304
God damn it, Dex.

289
00:23:09,388 --> 00:23:10,263
[gunshots]

290
00:23:12,599 --> 00:23:13,850
Okay, now. Go, go, go!

291
00:23:28,407 --> 00:23:29,282
[Dex grunts]

292
00:23:47,676 --> 00:23:50,178
[dispatcher over radio]
<i>Third floor, 2312 King Street.</i>

293
00:23:50,262 --> 00:23:52,097
<i>Two suspects, violent.</i>

294
00:23:53,223 --> 00:23:55,976
[officer 1 over radio]
<i>Roger that, dispatch. 2312 King Street...</i>

295
00:24:04,693 --> 00:24:06,194
[officer 2] Police! Hands in the air!

296
00:24:18,123 --> 00:24:19,958
I'm FBI. I have ID.

297
00:24:20,959 --> 00:24:23,753
If you look in my pocket,
you'll find my wallet.

298
00:24:25,964 --> 00:24:28,216
Two armed suspects broke into my home.

299
00:24:33,847 --> 00:24:36,057
[young Dex]<i> ...tried not to, but I liked--</i>

300
00:25:21,478 --> 00:25:24,814
All right, all right,
everybody, settle down.

301
00:25:24,898 --> 00:25:27,192
We're getting to the good part
of the evening.

302
00:25:27,275 --> 00:25:28,527
[man] You mean dessert?

303
00:25:28,610 --> 00:25:29,778
[crowd laughing]

304
00:25:29,861 --> 00:25:32,781
[speaker] As if you need
another freakin' cannoli, Mikey!

305
00:25:32,864 --> 00:25:34,241
[crowd laughing]

306
00:25:34,324 --> 00:25:36,409
[speaker] Our agenda tonight is simple.

307
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:39,037
Our endorsement of a candidate
for district attorney...

308
00:25:39,120 --> 00:25:40,747
[on recording]<i> It's Karen.</i>
<i>You know what to do.</i>

309
00:25:40,830 --> 00:25:43,375
Karen? Where the hell are you?

310
00:25:43,458 --> 00:25:44,417
[elevator dings]

311
00:25:47,254 --> 00:25:48,421
[metal detector beeps]

312
00:25:48,505 --> 00:25:51,466
-How did you get up here?
-I checked into a room.

313
00:25:51,550 --> 00:25:53,009
This floor FBI is personnel only.

314
00:25:53,093 --> 00:25:54,970
Hi, I'm Karen Page. I'm with the <i>Bulletin.</i>

315
00:25:55,053 --> 00:25:55,971
We know who you are.

316
00:25:56,054 --> 00:25:57,597
Well, I'd like to talk to him.

317
00:25:57,681 --> 00:25:59,099
[Lim] Not gonna happen.

318
00:25:59,182 --> 00:26:02,852
[scoffs] Under his agreement,
he's entitled to speak to the press.

319
00:26:02,936 --> 00:26:05,522
Unless you two wanna
make the call to violate that?

320
00:26:05,605 --> 00:26:08,358
Fisk and his lawyers have to sign off
on all press requests.

321
00:26:08,441 --> 00:26:12,320
They tell all you people to screw off.
You're wasting your time.

322
00:26:12,404 --> 00:26:15,198
All right.
Well, why don't you call his lawyers

323
00:26:15,282 --> 00:26:17,701
and tell them I want to give
Mr. Fisk a chance to comment

324
00:26:17,784 --> 00:26:20,412
on a story that I'm writing
about a Marlene Vistain?

325
00:26:21,246 --> 00:26:22,581
That's Fisk's mother.

326
00:26:22,664 --> 00:26:23,665
Shit.

327
00:26:24,457 --> 00:26:25,667
He actually had one?

328
00:26:27,627 --> 00:26:30,338
Go ahead. Call his lawyers. I'll wait.

329
00:26:35,510 --> 00:26:37,345
[Tower] Prosecutions
aren't the whole story.

330
00:26:37,429 --> 00:26:39,764
The vast majority of our caseload
never sees a jury,

331
00:26:39,848 --> 00:26:44,811
because we bring such strong cases to bear
that defendants plead guilty voluntarily.

332
00:26:44,894 --> 00:26:48,189
Which means more bad guys in jail
for less money.

333
00:26:48,273 --> 00:26:50,066
Something we all can agree on?

334
00:26:55,739 --> 00:26:59,367
Until you let them out of prison again.
Isn't that right, Mr. Tower?

335
00:26:59,451 --> 00:27:03,705
Because you sign off
on both kinds of deals, don't you, sir?

336
00:27:03,788 --> 00:27:05,415
Is that Foggy Nelson?

337
00:27:05,498 --> 00:27:06,541
Uh...

338
00:27:06,625 --> 00:27:07,959
Sure is, Mr. Gerlach.

339
00:27:08,043 --> 00:27:09,878
What are you doing, Foggy?

340
00:27:09,961 --> 00:27:13,340
I told your girlfriend if you ain't
on the ballot, you can't speak.

341
00:27:13,423 --> 00:27:17,552
But the Nelsons are members, too,
and this is an endorsement meeting.

342
00:27:17,636 --> 00:27:19,596
Members can ask questions,
isn't that right?

343
00:27:19,679 --> 00:27:21,890
It ain't gonna change the vote, Foggy.

344
00:27:21,973 --> 00:27:24,684
You're just holding up dessert
and pissing people off.

345
00:27:24,768 --> 00:27:25,894
[crowd laughing]

346
00:27:25,977 --> 00:27:29,022
I apologize to everyone.
This won't take long.

347
00:27:29,105 --> 00:27:30,732
Said every lawyer ever.

348
00:27:30,815 --> 00:27:32,859
[laughter]

349
00:27:32,942 --> 00:27:35,904
We can be long-winded, sure.
But I'm not billing anyone for this.

350
00:27:37,447 --> 00:27:40,492
I'm running my own
write-in campaign for DA.

351
00:27:40,575 --> 00:27:42,118
Most of you know that by now.

352
00:27:42,661 --> 00:27:44,621
I'm not running 'cause I expect to win.

353
00:27:45,246 --> 00:27:47,999
I'm running to hold him accountable.

354
00:27:48,083 --> 00:27:50,210
Debate is the soul of democracy.

355
00:27:50,794 --> 00:27:53,588
So why aren't you talking
about Wilson Fisk?

356
00:27:53,672 --> 00:27:55,465
Are you running for office, Mr. Tower,

357
00:27:55,548 --> 00:27:58,593
or are you running away
from responsibility for his situation?

358
00:27:59,761 --> 00:28:01,429
We've been here before, Mr. Nelson.

359
00:28:01,513 --> 00:28:05,225
Do you still claim to have no influence
over his release from prison

360
00:28:05,308 --> 00:28:07,185
to live among us here in the city again?

361
00:28:07,268 --> 00:28:10,355
The powers of my office
are limited to state law.

362
00:28:10,438 --> 00:28:13,692
Wilson Fisk's situation is
entirely under federal jurisdiction and--

363
00:28:13,775 --> 00:28:15,944
[Foggy] You mean crimes
he's already been sentenced for?

364
00:28:16,027 --> 00:28:16,861
Of course.

365
00:28:16,945 --> 00:28:21,616
But you can prosecute for crimes
he's committing right now, can't you?

366
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:22,742
What crimes?

367
00:28:22,826 --> 00:28:25,829
The man is locked up in FBI custody
24 hours a day.

368
00:28:26,913 --> 00:28:28,915
In a five-star hotel.

369
00:28:28,998 --> 00:28:31,251
Because he made a deal with the feds.

370
00:28:31,334 --> 00:28:36,047
Living in luxury as long as he gives up
major underworld figures.

371
00:28:36,131 --> 00:28:39,843
Which Fisk has done, time and again,
making this city safer.

372
00:28:39,926 --> 00:28:42,679
Or making his competition disappear.

373
00:28:43,972 --> 00:28:45,014
That's right.

374
00:28:46,349 --> 00:28:50,687
Wilson Fisk is informing
on carefully-selected targets.

375
00:28:50,770 --> 00:28:53,940
Using the government as his private army

376
00:28:54,023 --> 00:28:58,278
to reclaim his position at the center
of this city's criminal underworld.

377
00:28:58,361 --> 00:28:59,362
This is fantasy.

378
00:28:59,446 --> 00:29:02,741
No, it's a harsh reality.

379
00:29:04,576 --> 00:29:08,705
There are government officials
who are controlled by various criminals.

380
00:29:08,788 --> 00:29:10,290
What Wilson Fisk has done

381
00:29:10,373 --> 00:29:13,209
is take all those criminals
and turn them over to the FBI.

382
00:29:13,293 --> 00:29:16,504
And keep all those corrupt officials
for himself.

383
00:29:17,088 --> 00:29:23,595
He's planning to turn himself into a
one-stop shop for bribery and protection.

384
00:29:23,678 --> 00:29:25,722
It's all right here.

385
00:29:25,805 --> 00:29:27,182
[Tower] Mr. Nelson.

386
00:29:27,265 --> 00:29:30,977
As district attorney,
you can't just pander to a crowd.

387
00:29:31,060 --> 00:29:32,771
You have to prove your case.

388
00:29:32,854 --> 00:29:34,773
-I can.
-[Tower] No, you can't.

389
00:29:34,856 --> 00:29:35,857
My turn.

390
00:29:36,649 --> 00:29:40,320
At your fancy law firm,
what they teach is, "Create a fiction."

391
00:29:40,904 --> 00:29:43,531
What story does a jury need to hear?
Not what facts.

392
00:29:44,073 --> 00:29:46,451
I have been prosecuting for 13 years,

393
00:29:46,534 --> 00:29:49,454
and I can tell you
this is not how criminal law works.

394
00:29:49,537 --> 00:29:53,374
Moving speeches impress a crowd,
but they don't stand up in criminal court.

395
00:29:54,459 --> 00:29:56,836
I don't have your experience, Mr. Tower.

396
00:29:57,754 --> 00:29:59,380
It's true. But then again,

397
00:30:00,173 --> 00:30:04,636
I'm not jaded from doing the same thing
for too many years, either.

398
00:30:04,719 --> 00:30:07,555
I'm still passionate
about what the law can do.

399
00:30:08,348 --> 00:30:10,975
And that's a very powerful tool
to work with.

400
00:30:11,893 --> 00:30:14,604
Because when you get beyond the cold facts

401
00:30:14,687 --> 00:30:17,816
and really get worked up
about what you're doing, you can...

402
00:30:22,362 --> 00:30:23,363
Holy shit.

403
00:30:23,446 --> 00:30:25,156
I can't hear you.

404
00:30:25,240 --> 00:30:28,660
You can do what, Mr. Nelson?
Freeze up in front of a jury?

405
00:30:28,743 --> 00:30:30,453
[Tower laughing]

406
00:30:41,756 --> 00:30:42,799
[Karen scoffs]

407
00:30:43,508 --> 00:30:44,759
We'll be watching.

408
00:30:51,099 --> 00:30:51,933
[door closes]

409
00:30:52,016 --> 00:30:53,476
You gotta be kidding me.

410
00:31:12,287 --> 00:31:13,496
[Fisk] Ms. Page.

411
00:31:22,213 --> 00:31:26,384
I must admit, I'm surprised you're here.

412
00:31:30,889 --> 00:31:33,516
I suppose this qualifies as hard time?

413
00:31:33,600 --> 00:31:36,811
Yes, I'm sure all of this
is offensive to you,

414
00:31:37,353 --> 00:31:39,314
given our personal history.

415
00:31:41,733 --> 00:31:43,651
You mean the times
you tried to have me killed?

416
00:31:45,278 --> 00:31:47,488
Crimes for which I'm still paying.

417
00:31:48,948 --> 00:31:51,910
Yes. It's offensive.

418
00:32:01,294 --> 00:32:02,295
Tea?

419
00:32:04,631 --> 00:32:05,715
No, thank you.

420
00:32:06,966 --> 00:32:08,468
I'm not here for tea.

421
00:32:20,855 --> 00:32:21,856
Sit down.

422
00:32:23,816 --> 00:32:26,361
You came for words, at least.

423
00:32:28,321 --> 00:32:29,322
Yeah.

424
00:32:31,366 --> 00:32:33,117
Let's-- Let's have some words.

425
00:32:44,253 --> 00:32:46,798
You are not writing
an article about my mother.

426
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:50,802
I'm not?

427
00:32:55,348 --> 00:32:56,432
I could.

428
00:32:56,516 --> 00:32:58,184
To what end, Ms. Page?

429
00:32:58,851 --> 00:33:00,436
My distress?

430
00:33:01,020 --> 00:33:02,146
[Karen] Hmm.

431
00:33:02,230 --> 00:33:04,774
Doesn't actually sound that bad,
now that you say it.

432
00:33:05,358 --> 00:33:09,195
I do not welcome intrusions
into my privacy.

433
00:33:09,821 --> 00:33:11,489
Yet you invited me in?

434
00:33:12,907 --> 00:33:17,578
You worked for Ben Urich, didn't you?

435
00:33:17,662 --> 00:33:19,288
I believe he mentored you.

436
00:33:19,372 --> 00:33:21,332
Yes, before he was murdered.

437
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:25,962
A final lesson.
One you seem not to have understood.

438
00:33:27,380 --> 00:33:28,464
Is that a threat?

439
00:33:29,298 --> 00:33:31,009
It's an observation.

440
00:33:33,845 --> 00:33:35,263
Well, you're right.

441
00:33:37,265 --> 00:33:39,600
I'm not here to talk about your mother.

442
00:33:41,602 --> 00:33:43,980
I'd rather talk about what she told Ben.

443
00:33:46,065 --> 00:33:49,610
Actually, really,
rather, what she told us.

444
00:33:52,655 --> 00:33:56,701
See, I don't think you know,
but I was with him.

445
00:33:57,618 --> 00:33:59,203
It probably wasn't fair.

446
00:33:59,287 --> 00:34:04,167
Two trained journalists
working on a feeble old woman like that.

447
00:34:06,502 --> 00:34:07,837
It's easy to push her.

448
00:34:09,255 --> 00:34:11,174
Get her to say things she doesn't want to.

449
00:34:11,799 --> 00:34:12,800
Your point?

450
00:34:14,093 --> 00:34:16,637
She remembered a lot about your childhood.

451
00:34:16,721 --> 00:34:21,267
They say the oldest memories
stick around the longest.

452
00:34:22,393 --> 00:34:26,981
She remembered a lot of little things.
A lot of... embarrassing things.

453
00:34:28,024 --> 00:34:32,403
Seems like there were a lot of those,
weren't there, Willie?

454
00:34:36,199 --> 00:34:40,411
I'm sure your readers at the <i>Bulletin</i>
will be as entertained as you are.

455
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:43,873
No, we would never print those.

456
00:34:43,956 --> 00:34:46,125
We just pass them around the office.

457
00:34:47,376 --> 00:34:49,378
How is it around your office?

458
00:34:52,924 --> 00:34:54,717
I heard about your misfortune.

459
00:34:54,801 --> 00:34:57,303
Before it even happened, I'm sure.

460
00:34:58,221 --> 00:35:00,181
No, the story that we will print

461
00:35:00,264 --> 00:35:03,059
is her very detailed description
of your father.

462
00:35:03,142 --> 00:35:05,144
And how you murdered him.

463
00:35:05,228 --> 00:35:06,104
[inhales sharply]

464
00:35:06,938 --> 00:35:08,564
A hammer. At that age?

465
00:35:15,196 --> 00:35:19,951
Is there any part of you
that isn't broken, I wonder?

466
00:35:27,250 --> 00:35:28,960
[inhales deeply]

467
00:35:32,213 --> 00:35:33,673
[exhales deeply]

468
00:35:40,304 --> 00:35:41,722
[Fisk sighs]

469
00:35:49,981 --> 00:35:53,734
You asked me why I let you in.

470
00:35:55,403 --> 00:35:59,323
The reason is, Ms. Page,
I have a few questions of my own.

471
00:35:59,407 --> 00:36:01,868
You are a respected journalist,

472
00:36:01,951 --> 00:36:06,247
but at one time you were
merely a secretary at a law firm.

473
00:36:06,330 --> 00:36:08,249
To Matt Murdock, yes?

474
00:36:08,332 --> 00:36:09,458
Office manager.

475
00:36:09,542 --> 00:36:12,587
Intimately involved in his affairs, huh?

476
00:36:12,670 --> 00:36:14,255
His business affairs.

477
00:36:14,338 --> 00:36:15,506
Of course.

478
00:36:15,590 --> 00:36:21,762
Tell me, so at what point did you learn
about Mr. Murdock's secret life?

479
00:36:28,060 --> 00:36:29,061
Yeah.

480
00:36:29,896 --> 00:36:31,105
Thank you.

481
00:36:32,064 --> 00:36:33,691
Thank you, Ms. Page.

482
00:36:43,159 --> 00:36:44,160
[softly] Okay. Okay.

483
00:36:48,497 --> 00:36:49,874
You want secrets?

484
00:36:51,292 --> 00:36:53,294
I can tell you a secret, Wilson.

485
00:36:53,377 --> 00:36:56,255
Okay if I call you that? I feel like
we know each other well enough by now.

486
00:36:56,339 --> 00:36:58,174
-[Fisk] As you wish, Karen.
-Great.

487
00:37:00,468 --> 00:37:02,220
James Wesley.

488
00:37:05,264 --> 00:37:08,517
What was it like for you
when he disappeared?

489
00:37:10,353 --> 00:37:14,357
Really, it's those first 24 hours
that are the worst, aren't they?

490
00:37:15,358 --> 00:37:19,028
When you call and you call and you call,
and there's just no answer.

491
00:37:19,111 --> 00:37:20,780
It becomes an obsession.

492
00:37:22,865 --> 00:37:27,787
The calling. The never-ending loop
of a ghost's voice mail in your ear.

493
00:37:28,913 --> 00:37:29,914
You worry.

494
00:37:31,040 --> 00:37:32,083
You wonder.

495
00:37:32,708 --> 00:37:34,335
You swear, "God damn it,

496
00:37:34,418 --> 00:37:36,420
if he's still living,
I'm gonna kill him myself."

497
00:37:39,257 --> 00:37:40,800
Is that what it was like for you?

498
00:37:40,883 --> 00:37:42,385
Did you rage at him?

499
00:37:43,177 --> 00:37:45,179
'Cause you thought he betrayed you?

500
00:37:45,263 --> 00:37:47,098
Because I wonder
what would be worse for you. His duplicity or his death?

501
00:37:49,100 --> 00:37:51,644
[Fisk breathing shakily]

502
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:56,649
[softly] He died quickly.

503
00:37:57,233 --> 00:37:58,901
If you were wondering.

504
00:37:59,944 --> 00:38:01,529
Didn't suffer much.

505
00:38:02,363 --> 00:38:06,784
You see, Wilson, Matt Murdock isn't
the person you should be worried about.

506
00:38:08,160 --> 00:38:09,662
I killed Wesley.

507
00:38:11,289 --> 00:38:14,208
I shot him seven times.

508
00:38:14,292 --> 00:38:17,378
Because the clip ran out.
He deserved more.

509
00:38:18,296 --> 00:38:19,297
[yells]

510
00:38:19,839 --> 00:38:20,756
[Wellers] Don't move!

511
00:38:21,674 --> 00:38:23,426
[yells and groans]

512
00:38:24,135 --> 00:38:25,136
What? What?

513
00:38:34,770 --> 00:38:35,813
Foggy?

514
00:38:41,068 --> 00:38:42,320
Think of it as a compliment.

515
00:38:42,403 --> 00:38:44,530
That they actually thought
I would try to kill him?

516
00:38:44,613 --> 00:38:46,699
-I had to tell them something.
-No, Foggy, you didn't.

517
00:38:47,533 --> 00:38:49,243
You ruined it. I had him.

518
00:38:49,327 --> 00:38:51,829
Had him? Fisk would snap you like a twig.

519
00:38:51,912 --> 00:38:53,497
At least they'd have it on video.

520
00:38:55,791 --> 00:38:57,126
Was that really your plan?

521
00:38:58,044 --> 00:39:01,380
God damn it, Karen.
Don't turn into Matt on me.

522
00:39:05,009 --> 00:39:08,637
Look, I didn't want him to kill me.
Just come after me.

523
00:39:08,721 --> 00:39:10,514
Oh, good.

524
00:39:11,724 --> 00:39:14,518
-Well, I got the idea from you.
-Me?

525
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:16,896
All that talk about Tower
and catching him off guard,

526
00:39:16,979 --> 00:39:20,149
and I thought, "Yeah,
just get Fisk to stop thinking

527
00:39:20,232 --> 00:39:22,193
and reacting emotionally instead."

528
00:39:22,985 --> 00:39:25,363
I figured you were thinking
something like that.

529
00:39:25,905 --> 00:39:27,865
Not a bad plan, actually.

530
00:39:27,948 --> 00:39:30,868
Except for the part
where you have to hope the FBI comes in

531
00:39:30,951 --> 00:39:32,620
before that monster beats you to death.

532
00:39:32,703 --> 00:39:34,830
-Well, it doesn't matter now, does it?
-[elevator dings]

533
00:39:36,165 --> 00:39:37,833
How did you even know I was here?

534
00:39:38,459 --> 00:39:39,668
I know you.

535
00:39:39,752 --> 00:39:41,087
When you didn't come...

536
00:39:41,962 --> 00:39:45,883
I thought of some possibilities
and this was my nightmare scenario.

537
00:39:45,966 --> 00:39:47,593
So I pretty much counted on it.

538
00:39:48,386 --> 00:39:50,012
At least I took my shot.

539
00:39:50,096 --> 00:39:51,263
You took a shot.

540
00:39:51,847 --> 00:39:54,266
Tomorrow, there's gonna be
an army shooting back.

541
00:39:58,771 --> 00:40:01,107
The report, for your insurance.

542
00:40:01,732 --> 00:40:02,817
Thank you.

543
00:41:47,338 --> 00:41:48,672
[knock on door] Come with me.

544
00:42:02,353 --> 00:42:04,563
Yeah, yeah, another late one.

545
00:42:05,814 --> 00:42:09,693
I know, babe, but they're filing charges
against the Albanians tomorrow,

546
00:42:09,777 --> 00:42:12,238
and I never reviewed my account.

547
00:42:13,906 --> 00:42:16,325
Yeah, I'm not gonna make it home tonight.

548
00:42:19,370 --> 00:42:20,913
Kiss Sami for me.

549
00:42:23,165 --> 00:42:24,291
I love you, too.

550
00:42:42,560 --> 00:42:45,271
[breathing heavily]

551
00:42:51,068 --> 00:42:51,902
[grunts]

552
00:43:15,217 --> 00:43:16,885
[line ringing]

553
00:43:20,306 --> 00:43:21,307
Boss. Nadeem.

554
00:43:23,767 --> 00:43:25,144
Sorry to wake you.

555
00:43:27,980 --> 00:43:29,315
We need to talk.

556
00:44:01,764 --> 00:44:03,140
[elevator dings]

557
00:44:26,705 --> 00:44:27,706
After you.

558
00:44:41,178 --> 00:44:44,264
This was here the whole time?

559
00:44:44,348 --> 00:44:45,349
[Fisk] Yes. We, um...

560
00:44:52,314 --> 00:44:53,482
I have a problem.

561
00:44:54,817 --> 00:44:56,318
Nadeem knows.

562
00:44:56,402 --> 00:44:57,736
I know he does.

563
00:44:58,821 --> 00:45:01,240
We will take care of the problem.

564
00:45:09,123 --> 00:45:10,165
Dex...

565
00:45:12,835 --> 00:45:15,295
rage cannot stay inside.

566
00:45:17,131 --> 00:45:22,177
It needs to go somewhere...
or it becomes a poison.

567
00:45:22,261 --> 00:45:24,388
It will kill you from within.

568
00:45:24,471 --> 00:45:30,060
I find that when this rage
cannot stay buried in me

569
00:45:30,144 --> 00:45:31,812
for one more second...

570
00:45:32,855 --> 00:45:38,986
that a primal scream...
is the only satisfying release.

571
00:45:41,864 --> 00:45:42,865
Yes. Yeah.

572
00:45:48,829 --> 00:45:52,332
[screams]

573
00:46:12,144 --> 00:46:14,188
[young Dex over recording]
<i>I like making things happen</i>

574
00:46:14,271 --> 00:46:16,398
<i>without anybody knowing</i>
<i>it's me who did it.</i>

575
00:46:17,274 --> 00:46:20,360
[Mercer over recording]
<i>Let's do our exercise. Close your eyes.</i>

576
00:46:20,444 --> 00:46:21,862
[Matt] He didn't have any parents.

577
00:46:21,945 --> 00:46:23,739
[young Dex] <i>I'm digging a hole.</i>

578
00:46:24,698 --> 00:46:26,033
Spent a lot of time fighting.

579
00:46:26,116 --> 00:46:27,785
[young Dex]<i> Buried my anger in the ground.</i>

580
00:46:27,868 --> 00:46:28,952
-[Mercer] <i>Good.</i>
-Angry.

581
00:46:29,036 --> 00:46:33,373
-[Mercer] <i>Now cover it with dirt.</i>
-[young Dex] <i>Okay. But, Dr. Mercer?</i>

582
00:46:34,041 --> 00:46:36,335
-Go ahead and say it.
-[young Dex] <i>I want to open the box.</i>

583
00:46:36,418 --> 00:46:38,003
I promised to keep my mouth shut.

584
00:46:38,086 --> 00:46:40,422
-But you want to say it sounds familiar.
-Does it?

585
00:46:45,260 --> 00:46:48,013
I didn't have anyone either,
but I'm nothing like him.

586
00:46:49,890 --> 00:46:52,851
The tapes make it sound
like he was a killer at a young age.

587
00:46:52,935 --> 00:46:54,269
The guy's a psychopath.

588
00:46:58,524 --> 00:47:00,234
And I had a chance today.

589
00:47:01,568 --> 00:47:04,238
A shot to catch him off guard,
and I blew it.

590
00:47:05,447 --> 00:47:07,199
You did what you thought was right.

591
00:47:07,825 --> 00:47:10,118
You kept your word to Agent Nadeem.

592
00:47:10,202 --> 00:47:11,203
Yeah.

593
00:47:13,539 --> 00:47:15,332
And how many people will die
because of it?

594
00:47:35,227 --> 00:47:38,397
I don't know if I have the strength
to get through this.

595
00:47:39,314 --> 00:47:40,274
[Matt grunting]

596
00:47:40,858 --> 00:47:42,609
He's so stubborn.

597
00:47:43,610 --> 00:47:45,946
Full of fury and foolish pride.

598
00:47:47,823 --> 00:47:48,907
Please...

599
00:47:50,075 --> 00:47:51,577
watch over him.

600
00:47:53,370 --> 00:47:57,291
Keep him from making the same
damned mistake that took you from us.

601
00:47:58,250 --> 00:48:00,836
Our son is too much like you, Jack.

602
00:48:07,426 --> 00:48:08,635
Mom?

603
00:48:08,719 --> 00:48:10,137
Mom.

604
00:48:13,390 --> 00:48:14,391
No.

